-- French Stocks Advance, Paced by Credit Agricole, BNP Paribas and Faurecia
-- David Altaner
-- 2010-06-30T16:35:22Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-30/alstom-faurecia-safran-societe-generale-total-french-equity-preview.html

          
          
             France’s benchmark CAC 40 Index rose
9.9, or 0.3 percent, to 3,442.89 in Paris. The SBF 120 Index
gained 0.2 percent.  
 The following are among the most active stocks traded in
France today.  
 Credit Agricole SA  (ACA FP) gained 3.4 percent to 8.64
euros.  BNP Paribas SA  (BNP FP) increased 2.3 percent to 44.77
euros. The European Central Bank said it will lend banks 131.9
billion euros ($162 billion) for three months, less than
economists had forecast, as a landmark yearlong loan expires.  
 Faurecia SA  (EO FP) rose 2.3 percent to 13.22 euros.
Europe’s biggest maker of car interiors agreed to buy another
four plants from Plastal, an insolvent German plastic auto-parts
maker, taking on supply contracts for Ford Motor Co., Volkswagen
AG and Fiat SpA’s IVECO truck unit.  
 France Telecom SA  (FTE FP) The French phone company dropped
1.1 percent to 14.29 euros after Goldman Sachs Group Inc. cut
its recommendation to “neutral” from “buy.”  
